Over the past 2.5 weeks of reporting, it appears that there have been 6424 additional cases. Although the numbers had decreased, the new period increased averaging about 357 cases PER DAY. The low case fatality rate might suggest that some of the diarrhea may be non-cholera. Although the daily rate had dropped significantly, this many new diarrhea cases per day remains substantial. There had been a slowing of cases during the 3-month period of January-March 2017 as well. The daily rate seems to be moving upwards a bit.

A map of Yemen: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=5868961,126. - Mod.LL]

******
[2] Saudi Arabia
Date: Thu 21 Jun 2018
Source: Jazan News [in Arabic, trans. Mod.MM, edited]
http://www.jazannews.org/include/plugins/news/news.php?action=s&id=49964


In a press release the Ministry of Health of Jizan province reported 11 cases of cholera after initial lab investigations, which await further confirmation. All the 11 cholera cases were related to illegal immigrants, were focused in Beni Malik suburban area, and they were hospitalized and given the needed care, according to the MOH statement.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
via
ProMED-MENA
<promed-mena@promedmail.org>

[Cholera may actively be exchanged across the Yemeni-Saudi borders due to the prevailing insecurity in this area which favors illegal immigrants trafficking from war torn Yemen to reach the oil rich countries, such as Saudi Arabia. The country of origin of the affected expatriate cases (called wafideen in Arabic, versus citizens) is not clear in the newswire above. However, taking into account the close proximity of Jizan city to Yemen, one might assume these cases may have crossed the border from Yemen as Jizan is one of the gates into Saudi Arabia. - Mod.MM]

[Jizan, also spelled Jazan, Gizan or Gazan, is a port city and the capital of Jizan Region, which lies in the southwest corner of Saudi Arabia and directly north of the border with Yemen. - Mod.LL

HealthMap/ProMED-mail map
